# Engram Local Memory

## 2026-05-30 — PR #18 CI/test follow-up after Claude handoff

Durable, non-obvious lessons:
- Waited for Claude to stop modifying the worktree before intervening on
  `fix/ci-test-failures`; the branch was already tied to PR #18 and GitHub CI
  showed failing `typescript` and `swift-unit` checks.
- The Linux TypeScript coverage failure was not a source boundary violation.
  `tests/scripts/swift-boundary-scripts.test.ts` invoked
  `scripts/check-swift-module-boundaries.sh`, which exits early when `xcodegen`
  is absent. The test now skips only when `command -v xcodegen` fails. Use
  `bash -c`, not `bash -lc`, for that probe, because login shells can re-add
  Homebrew paths and mask the no-xcodegen CI case.
- The macOS Swift CI post-test check used `grep -q '** TEST SUCCEEDED **'`.
  BSD grep treats that as an invalid regex; fixed the workflow to use
  `grep -Fq` so the xcodebuild success marker is matched literally.
- `FTSRebuildPolicyTests.readCounts` could pass locally but hit Swift's
  "unable to type-check this expression in reasonable time" on CI. Splitting
  the large tuple into named local values preserved behavior and removed the
  type-check hot spot.
- A later PR #18 `swift-unit` rerun exposed an Xcode 16.4 compatibility break
  that local Xcode 26.4 did not catch: empty `nonisolated deinit` in
  `ReplayState` requires experimental `IsolatedDeinit` on the runner. Removing
  the empty deinit is the best compatibility fix; do not enable an experimental
  frontend flag for a no-op destructor.
- Two test-quality regressions from the handoff were restored:
  `release-verify` forbidden-artifact hygiene stays cross-platform while
  plist/signing assertions remain macOS-only, and the resume API test uses a
  `cursor` session so it can keep asserting the deterministic `open` command
  instead of accepting either a command or an error.
- Verification this session: targeted no-xcodegen Vitest skip under
  `PATH=/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin`; targeted TS tests for server,
  release-verify, and Swift boundary scripts; full `npm run test:coverage`
  (1424 pass); `npm run typecheck:test`; `npm run lint`; targeted
  `EngramCoreTests/FTSRebuildPolicyTests`; full local Swift unit run with
  227 tests, 1 skipped, 0 failures; literal `grep -Fq` success-marker smoke
  against `/tmp/engram-swift-unit-final.log`.
- GitHub PR #18 rerun after `90f869dc`: lint, dead-code, fixture-check, and
  typescript passed; swift-unit then failed only on the Xcode 16.4
  `nonisolated deinit` compiler error above.
- GitHub PR #18 rerun after `5f572403`: compile progressed past the deinit
  issue; lint, dead-code, fixture-check, and typescript passed; swift-unit
  then exposed two more CI-only timing/fixture problems. `runGit` could return
  late output if the semaphore wake lagged past a very small timeout, so it now
  also checks elapsed wall time. `UnixSocketFixtureServer` no longer shares one
  `JSONDecoder` across concurrent handler tasks, and the concurrent socket
  test has a bounded client timeout to avoid opaque one-minute XCTest restarts.
- Pre-existing untracked `docs/full-review-report.md` was left untouched.

## 2026-05-27 — AI title/summary observability defect fixes (5-round review)

Durable, non-obvious lessons:
- The AI title/summary service path added in `168b4abc` had a critical bug:
  `EngramServiceCommandHandler.aiContext` read the transcript with
  `SELECT content FROM sessions_fts WHERE session_id = ? LIMIT 1`, but
  `sessions_fts` stores ONE ROW PER MESSAGE (see
  `IndexJobRunner.buildSearchContent` → `replaceFtsContent`). So the LLM only
  saw the first message of every multi-message session. Fixed by aggregating
  all rows `ORDER BY rowid` and joining with `\n`.
- Non-obvious and previously misleading: `SessionSnapshotWriter.searchText()` /
  `embeddingText()` are CHANGE-DETECTION ONLY (compared to set the
  `.searchTextChanged` / `.embeddingTextChanged` flags). They are NOT written
  into `sessions_fts.content`. The real FTS content comes from
  `IndexJobRunner.replaceFtsContent`. So `168b4abc` prepending `snapshotHash`
  to those strings does not pollute keyword search.
- `titleProvider` enum is only `ollama|openai|dashscope|custom` (no
  anthropic/gemini); all non-ollama title providers are OpenAI-compatible, so
  the service's OpenAI-only `chat()` is correct for titles. By contrast
  `aiProtocol` (summary) may be anthropic/gemini, but the Swift service only
  implements the OpenAI chat shape, so those protocols silently fall back to
  native summaries. That is a known gap, not a regression (pre-PR summary was
  always native).
- The service summary now honors `summaryLanguage` / `summaryMaxSentences` /
  `summaryStyle` / `summaryPrompt` via `ServiceAIClient.renderSummaryPrompt`,
  which mirrors `renderPromptTemplate` in `src/core/ai-client.ts`. Previously
  the prompt was hardcoded Chinese + "三句话".
- Tooling gotchas confirmed this session:
  - `npm run lint` can exit 1 as an rtk-wrapper artifact (it tries to parse
    biome output as ESLint JSON and fails). Verify lint with
    `./node_modules/.bin/biome check .` directly — it reported 0 errors.
  - `EngramServiceCoreTests` run under the `EngramServiceCore` xcode SCHEME,
    not a standalone test scheme, and they are NOT in the `Engram` scheme's
    test plan (`-only-testing:EngramServiceCoreTests/...` under `Engram` fails
    with "isn't a member of the specified test plan or scheme").
- Verification this session: `npx vitest run tests/core/config.test.ts
  tests/core/ai-client.test.ts tests/core/title-generator.test.ts` → 63 pass;
  `npm run build` (tsc) exit 0; `xcodebuild -scheme Engram build-for-testing`
  exit 0; `xcodebuild -scheme EngramServiceCore test` → 85 pass (incl. 4 new
  AI tests); `-only-testing:EngramTests/DatabaseManagerTests` → 43 pass.

## 2026-05-25 — Codex v0.133 MCP protocol compatibility fix

Durable, non-obvious lessons:
- Codex v0.133 initializes MCP servers with `protocolVersion: 2025-06-18`.
  EngramMCP previously accepted older versions only and returned
  `-32602 Unsupported protocolVersion`, causing Codex TUI to show
  `MCP startup incomplete (failed: engram)` and `Tools: (none)` for the
  `/Users/bing/.engram/bin/engram-mcp` server.
- The correct reproduction is a real Codex TUI startup or a stdio initialize
  smoke against the installed shim, not merely running the app:
  send `initialize` with `2025-06-18`, then `notifications/initialized`, then
  `tools/list`. A healthy install returns `protocolVersion: 2025-06-18` and the
  full Engram tool registry.
- Fix landed in `70170e0e fix: support codex mcp protocol 2025-06-18` by adding
  `2025-06-18` to `MCPStdioServer.supportedProtocolVersions` plus an executable
  regression test in `EngramMCPExecutableTests`.
- Local deployment after the fix installed `/Applications/Engram.app` build
  `0.1.0 (691)`. Verification evidence: Team ID `J25GS8J4XM`, Hardened Runtime
  present, installed shim smoke passes, `Engram` and `EngramService` run at
  normal CPU/RSS, and `EngramMCP` exits after the client closes instead of
  staying resident.

## 2026-05-23 — TDD closeout of all open roadmap items

Durable, non-obvious lessons:
- Hosted `EngramTests` (TEST_HOST = Engram.app) fail to LOAD with a Team-ID
  mismatch ("mapping process and mapped file have different Team IDs") under
  default signing, because the test bundle and host app get different teams.
  Run with `DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=J25GS8J4XM` to make host + bundle consistent:
  `xcodebuild test -scheme Engram -destination platform=macOS DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=J25GS8J4XM`.
  Keychain has two teams: Apple Development cert → AE7P4G8656; Developer ID /
  Distribution → J25GS8J4XM. `project.yml` pins the app to J25GS8J4XM with a
  generic "Apple Development" identity, so AE7P4G8656 (Automatic) errors with
  "No Mac Development certificate ... with a private key". Use J25GS8J4XM.
- The indexer-parity fixture `tests/fixtures/indexer-parity/expected-db-checksums.json`
  is GENERATED by `scripts/gen-indexer-parity-fixtures.ts` (runs the Node
  Indexer). `IndexerParityTests.testSwiftIndexerMatchesNodeDBChecksumFixtureForCodex`
  compares the Swift indexer's `sessions` ROWS (not a sha256) against it. Any
  Swift indexer output change (e.g. new `generated_title`) must update BOTH the
  committed fixture AND the generator (mirror the derivation) or a `--out` regen
  silently reverts the fixture and the Swift test re-breaks.
- `git_repos` was created by migration but never written; the Repos/Workspace
  page was dormant. `RepoDiscovery.discover` (EngramCoreWrite) now populates it
  from session `cwd`s and is called in `EngramServiceRunner`'s recent-scan loop.
- After adding ANY Swift file (including test files), run `xcodegen generate`
  before `xcodebuild`. `-only-testing:EngramTests/NewClass` silently runs nothing
  if the class isn't in the regenerated project (cost me a phantom "6 vs 7
  tests" until I noticed the new test class never registered).
- rtk hijacks plain `grep`/`find` with certain flags (`-G`, `-path`, piping into
  a second `grep`) → spurious "Bun is a fast JavaScript runtime" output. Use
  `git grep` / the Read tool, and avoid `cmd | grep` pipelines.

## 2026-05-22 — Round-5 closeout + EngramUITests fully restored

Durable, non-obvious lessons (not derivable from code alone):
- Swift test topology is split across schemes. `xcodebuild -scheme Engram test`
  runs ONLY EngramCoreTests + EngramTests. Service/MCP suites need their own
  schemes: `-scheme EngramServiceCore` (EngramServiceCoreTests) and
  `-scheme EngramMCPTests`. EngramUITests are in the Engram scheme but are
  environment-sensitive (need the seeded fixture). A green "Engram scheme" run
  does NOT cover service/MCP tests.
- EngramUITests fixture wiring: the EngramUITests target must bundle
  `macos/test-fixtures` (holds `test-index.sqlite`), not `../tests/fixtures`;
  `AppEnvironment.fromCommandLine` must let `--test-mode` win over the
  `XCTestConfigurationFilePath` host check; regenerate the DB via
  `npm run generate:fixtures` after schema changes.
- macOS 26 SwiftUI <-> XCUITest accessibility: `descendants(matching: .any)[id]`
  forces a full deep AX snapshot that can stack-overflow/crash the app — prefer
  typed collection queries (`buttons[id]`/`groups[id]`/`scrollViews[id]`).
  SwiftUI's a11y merge heuristic can collapse a container's children (container
  with a decorative sibling + `.accessibilityIdentifier`), hiding them from
  XCUITest; add `.accessibilityElement(children: .contain)` to re-expose.
- Round-5 fresh-angle review closeout: 61 findings fixed + EngramUITests back to
  0 failures. See CHANGELOG and commits `a1f6369e` / `9eb932fc` /
  `cfae3ea3`.

## 2026-05-21 — Full remediation ship after multi-agent review

- Starting point: `docs/superpowers/reports/2026-05-20-engram-review-findings.md`
  contained 27 verified findings from Codex subagents plus Gemini leads. The
  remediation branch closed all 27 and recorded evidence in
  `docs/superpowers/reports/2026-05-20-engram-review-resolution.md`.
- Provider/parser contract is now explicit: Swift product adapters are the
  implementation; TypeScript adapters are dev/reference/fixture tooling.
  `tests/fixtures/adapter-parity/**` is the golden parity corpus.
- Antigravity CLI, Command Code, and Qoder were the final focused providers:
  Antigravity CLI reads `~/.gemini/antigravity-cli/brain/` and still supports
  legacy Antigravity cache mapping; Command Code covers `tool-call.input` and
  `tool-call.args`; Qoder covers nested `subagents/` parent detection without
  false positives for project-level `subagents/` folders.
- Transcript display parity rule: Swift App, Swift MCP, Swift Service export,
  and Swift HTTP transcript endpoints return only non-empty `user` /
  `assistant` body messages. Tool, system, event, and subagent notification rows
  remain for indexing/statistics/diagnostics, but do not render as ordinary chat
  bubbles.
- Two Polycli review rounds were run with available providers
  `gemini`, `claude`, `copilot`, `minimax`, `cmd`, and `agy`. Actionable round-2
  issues fixed: Qoder parent detection outside `/Users`, whitespace/blank
  transcript filtering across MCP/export, blank assistant indexing stats, noop
  cost-row model refresh, and Xcode project worktree-name leakage.
- Final verification before ship:
  - `npm run check:adapter-parity-fixtures` passed.
  - Targeted Antigravity/Command Code/Qoder + web/API fixture tests passed:
    6 files, 115 tests.
  - Full `npm test` passed: 120 files, 1342 tests.
  - `npm run typecheck:test`, `npm run knip`, `npm run build`, and
    `npm audit --audit-level=high --json` passed with 0 high/critical issues.
  - Swift AdapterParity, MCP source schema/transcript, and ServiceCore
    HTTP/export display parity selected tests passed.
  - `macos/scripts/build-release.sh` archived successfully; local
    Developer-ID export hit the known exportOptions limitation, then fell back
    to the signed archive app. `/Applications/Engram.app` was replaced,
    codesign verified, and `Engram` + `EngramService` + `EngramMCP` were running.
- Git closeout: local and remote were reduced to a single `main` branch at
  `83f096c3 fix: harden provider parser parity`. `origin/main` had unrelated
  public-release history, so it was intentionally replaced with
  `--force-with-lease` after inspection. Temporary remote `codex/*`, backup,
  and `public-main` branches were deleted after confirming tags/coverage; local
  worktrees and old local branches were also removed.

## 2026-05-10 — Recent indexing must scan all active local session sources

- Root cause: `EngramServiceRunner` called `writer.indexRecentSessions()`, but
  `EngramDatabaseIndexer.indexRecentSessions()` defaulted to
  `SessionAdapterFactory.recentCodexAdapters()`, so the service's periodic
  recent scan indexed Codex only. Recently updated Claude JSONL files under
  `~/.claude/projects/` were invisible unless a full scan or source-specific
  path handled them.
- Fix: `indexRecentSessions()` now uses
  `SessionAdapterFactory.recentActiveAdapters()`. Codex still uses recent dated
  roots; file-backed sources such as Claude Code, Gemini, OpenCode, Cursor,
  Qwen, Kimi, Cline, VS Code, Windsurf, Antigravity, and Copilot are wrapped in
  `RecentlyModifiedSessionAdapter` and filtered by backing file mtime.
- Virtual locators must resolve to their backing file for mtime filtering:
  OpenCode-style `db.sqlite::sessionId` and Cursor-style
  `db.sqlite?composer=...` are handled explicitly.
- Service cadence is now immediate scan on startup, then every 5 minutes.
- Production verification after deploying `/Applications/Engram.app`:
  `/Users/bing/.claude/projects/-Users-bing--NetWork--Safeline/00bca506-271f-4f5c-92b4-c8e088696aae.jsonl`
  entered `~/.engram/index.sqlite` as `claude-code`, project `Safeline`.
  Follow-up DB check showed `message_count=1250` and
  `indexed_at=2026-05-10T15:25:39Z`; `EngramMCP get_session` could read the
  session transcript.
- Verification commands used during the fix:
  - `xcodebuild test -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme EngramCoreTests -only-testing:EngramCoreTests/IndexerParityTests`
    passed 16 tests.
  - `xcodebuild build -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme EngramService`
    passed.
  - Release deploy build passed and `/Applications/Engram.app` was replaced
    after stopping the old app/helper processes.

## 2026-05-08 — Swift-only cutover: drop stale Node schema compat gate

- The `scripts/db/check-swift-schema-compat.ts` gate was a Stage 0-4 migration
  guard, not a valid Swift-only correctness condition.
- It compared Swift-created SQLite schema against the old TypeScript
  `src/core/db.ts` reference schema and failed on `sessions.indexed_at`
  default drift (`''` vs `datetime('now')`), effectively forcing Swift to
  preserve Node defaults after the Node runtime had already been removed from
  the product path.
- Resolution: delete `scripts/db/check-swift-schema-compat.ts`, delete its
  dedicated Vitest coverage, and remove the GitHub Actions step after
  `swift-unit`.
- Verification recorded at removal time:
  - `rg "check-swift-schema-compat" .github package.json scripts tests`
    returned no active references.
  - `npm run test` passed: 112 files, 1272 tests.
  - `npm run build` passed.
- Keep TypeScript/npm development and fixture tooling separate from product
  runtime Node. Do not reintroduce Node schema compatibility as a Swift-only
  gate unless there is an explicit, current cross-runtime support requirement.

## 2026-05-09 — Current next-dev baseline after noise cleanup

- Product runtime baseline: native Swift `Engram.app` + `EngramService` +
  `EngramMCP`. TypeScript/npm remains development/reference/fixture tooling.
- Project move/archive/undo/batch are no longer fail-closed Stage 4 debt; they
  route through the native Swift service migration pipeline.
- Agent/session grouping work should start in Swift product code:
  - Swift adapters: `macos/Shared/EngramCore/Adapters/Sources/`
  - Swift indexing/backfills: `macos/EngramCoreWrite/Indexing/`
  - Service command surface: `macos/EngramService/Core/`
  - MCP routing: `macos/EngramMCP/Core/MCPToolRegistry.swift`
- Polycli provider sessions from `qwen`, `kimi`, `pi`, `copilot`,
  `opencode`, and `gemini-cli` now have startup/indexer handling for health
  pings, review probes, stage-fact probes, and same-cwd near-concurrent child
  sessions. These should be classified as dispatched/skip and, where possible,
  linked to the host session.
- OpenCode session size should be per payload/session, not the whole provider
  SQLite DB file size.
- Verification baseline for the 2026-05-08/09 cleanup:
  - Swift targeted tests for startup backfills/indexer parity passed.
  - `npm run test` passed: 112 files, 1272 tests.
  - `npm run build` passed.

## 2026-05-09 — Session detail child-agent list must not consume transcript viewport

- `SessionDetailView` must keep the main transcript readable even when a parent
  session has dozens of child/provider sessions.
- The Agent Sessions section should default to a compact collapsed header.
  Expanded content must be bounded by an internal scroll area instead of
  growing the outer layout and shrinking the transcript.
- This is especially important for Polycli health/review fan-outs where a
  single parent can have many qwen/kimi/pi/copilot/opencode child sessions.
